# Define dataset directory
DATASET = "2750"

# Get class labels dynamically from the directory structure
LABELS = [name for name in os.listdir(DATASET) if os.path.isdir(os.path.join(DATASET, name))]
print("Class Labels:", LABELS)

Class Labels: ['AnnualCrop', 'Forest', 'HerbaceousVegetation', 'Highway', 'Industrial', 'Pasture', 'PermanentCrop', 'Residential', 'River', 'SeaLake']
In [3]:
# Prepare data for training and testing
BATCH_SIZE = 64
INPUT_SHAPE = (64, 64, 3)
CLASS_MODE = 'categorical'

# Map each image path to its class label
data = {}
for label in LABELS:
    class_dir = os.path.join(DATASET, label)
    if os.path.exists(class_dir):
        for img in os.listdir(class_dir):
            img_path = os.path.join(class_dir, img)
            if os.path.isfile(img_path):
                data[img_path] = label
    else:
        print(f"Warning: Directory {class_dir} does not exist.")

X = pd.Series(list(data.keys()))
y = pd.Series(list(data.values()))
In [4]:
# Split data into training and test sets, and then into training and validation sets
split = StratifiedShuffleSplit(n_splits=1, test_size=0.2, random_state=69)
for train_idx, test_idx in split.split(X, y):
    train_paths = X.iloc[train_idx]
    train_labels = y.iloc[train_idx]
    test_paths = X.iloc[test_idx]
    test_labels = y.iloc[test_idx]

    val_split = StratifiedShuffleSplit(n_splits=1, test_size=0.1, random_state=69)
    for train_idx, val_idx in val_split.split(train_paths, train_labels):
        train_paths_final = train_paths.iloc[train_idx]
        train_labels_final = train_labels.iloc[train_idx]
        val_paths = train_paths.iloc[val_idx]
        val_labels = train_labels.iloc[val_idx]
In [5]:
# Create ImageDataGenerators for data augmentation and preprocessing
train_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255, rotation_range=20, width_shift_range=0.2,
                                   height_shift_range=0.2, shear_range=0.2, zoom_range=0.2,
                                   horizontal_flip=True, fill_mode='nearest')

val_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255)
test_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255)

# Create data generators using flow_from_dataframe
train_generator = train_datagen.flow_from_dataframe(
    dataframe=pd.DataFrame({'filename': train_paths_final, 'class': train_labels_final}),
    x_col='filename',
    y_col='class',
    target_size=(INPUT_SHAPE[0], INPUT_SHAPE[1]),
    batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
    class_mode=CLASS_MODE,
    shuffle=True
)

val_generator = val_datagen.flow_from_dataframe(
    dataframe=pd.DataFrame({'filename': val_paths, 'class': val_labels}),
    x_col='filename',
    y_col='class',
    target_size=(INPUT_SHAPE[0], INPUT_SHAPE[1]),
    batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
    class_mode=CLASS_MODE,
    shuffle=True
)

test_generator = test_datagen.flow_from_dataframe(
    dataframe=pd.DataFrame({'filename': test_paths, 'class': test_labels}),
    x_col='filename',
    y_col='class',
    target_size=(INPUT_SHAPE[0], INPUT_SHAPE[1]),
    batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
    class_mode=CLASS_MODE,
    shuffle=False
)

In [7]:
from tensorflow.keras import Input

# Define CNN model with Input layer
model = Sequential([
    # Input layer
    Input(shape=INPUT_SHAPE),

    # First convolutional block
    Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same'),
    BatchNormalization(),
    MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),

    # Second convolutional block
    Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same'),
    BatchNormalization(),
    MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),

    # Third convolutional block
    Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same'),
    BatchNormalization(),
    MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),

    # Fourth convolutional block
    Conv2D(256, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same'),
    BatchNormalization(),
    MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),

    # Fifth convolutional block
    Conv2D(512, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same'),
    BatchNormalization(),
    MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),

    # Flatten and fully connected layers
    Flatten(),
    Dense(512, activation='relu'),
    Dropout(0.5),
    Dense(256, activation='relu'),
    Dropout(0.5),
    Dense(len(LABELS), activation='softmax')  # Use the number of labels for the output layer
])

from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping, ModelCheckpoint, ReduceLROnPlateau, TensorBoard, CSVLogger
import os
import datetime

# Define callbacks
callbacks = [
    # Early stopping to prevent overfitting
    EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=10, restore_best_weights=True),

    # Save the best model during training (updated to .keras extension)
    ModelCheckpoint('best_model.keras', monitor='val_loss', save_best_only=True),

    # Reduce learning rate when the validation loss plateaus
    ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor='val_loss', factor=0.2, patience=3, min_lr=1e-6),

    # Log training metrics to TensorBoard
    TensorBoard(log_dir=os.path.join("logs", "fit", datetime.datetime.now().strftime("%Y%m%d-%H%M%S")), histogram_freq=1),

    # Log training metrics to a CSV file
    CSVLogger('training_log.csv', append=True)
]

from sklearn.metrics import precision_recall_curve, average_precision_score
from sklearn.preprocessing import label_binarize
from itertools import cycle


# Define number of classes and colors
n_classes = len(test_generator.class_indices)
colors = cycle(['blue', 'red', 'green', 'orange', 'purple', 'cyan', 'magenta', 'yellow', 'black', 'brown'])

# Binarize the labels
true_labels_bin = label_binarize(true_labels, classes=range(n_classes))
predicted_labels_bin = best_model.predict(test_generator)

# Plotting the Precision-Recall Curve
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))

for i, color in zip(range(n_classes), colors):
    precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(true_labels_bin[:, i], predicted_labels_bin[:, i])
    average_precision = average_precision_score(true_labels_bin[:, i], predicted_labels_bin[:, i])

    plt.plot(recall, precision, color=color, lw=2,
             label=f'Class {list(test_generator.class_indices.keys())[i]} (AP = {average_precision:.2f})')

plt.xlabel('Recall')
plt.ylabel('Precision')
plt.title('Precision-Recall Curve')
plt.legend(loc='upper right')
plt.show()

from PIL import Image
import numpy as np

def preprocess_image(image_path, target_size=(64, 64)):
    # Load the image
    image = Image.open(image_path)
    
    # Resize the image
    image = image.resize(target_size)
    
    # Convert image to numpy array and normalize
    image_array = np.array(image) / 255.0
    
    # Add batch dimension
    image_array = np.expand_dims(image_array, axis=0)
    
    return image_array

# Example usage
